# CI Reflect Helper — Pseudocode

```csharp
public async Task<ReflectResult> StoreCiBuildReflectionAsync(
    string namespaceName,
    string topic,                  // e.g. "ci-build-outcome"
    string buildSummary,
    DateOnly today)
{
    // Deterministic ID per topic-per-day so re-runs upsert instead of duplicating
    var memoryId = $"reflect-{topic}-{today:yyyy-MM-dd}";

    // 1. Check whether today's reflection already exists
    var existing = await engram.GetMemoryAsync(namespaceName, memoryId);

    if (existing != null)
    {
        // 3a. Duplicate scenario — append/merge instead of clobbering
        var mergedText = existing.Text
            + "\n\n--- additional run @ " + DateTimeOffset.UtcNow.ToString("o") + " ---\n"
            + buildSummary;

        await engram.StoreMemoryAsync(new StoreRequest {
            Namespace = namespaceName,
            Id        = memoryId,           // upsert on same ID
            Text      = mergedText,
            Category  = "retrospective",
            Lifecycle = "stm"
        });
    }
    else
    {
        // 2. First reflection of the day for this topic
        await engram.ReflectAsync(new ReflectRequest {
            Namespace = namespaceName,
            Topic     = topic,
            Id        = memoryId,           // pin the ID so verify is deterministic
            Text      = buildSummary
        });
    }

    // 3. Verify-by-read — fail the CI step if the memory isn't readable back
    var stored = await engram.GetMemoryAsync(namespaceName, memoryId);
    if (stored == null)
        throw new InvalidOperationException($"Reflection {memoryId} not persisted");

    return new ReflectResult(memoryId, stored.Lifecycle, wasUpsert: existing != null);
}
```

# Answers to your specific questions

**What ID will the stored memory have?**
Whatever you pass — and you *should* pass a deterministic one like `reflect-ci-build-outcome-2026-05-06`. If you let `reflect` mint its own ID, you typically get a UUID/hash, which makes "find today's reflection" impossible without a separate search. Pinning the ID makes verify-by-read trivial.

**What lifecycle state will it be in?**
`stm` (short-term memory) — that's the default for any newly stored memory per the project's lifecycle rules. CI build outcomes are usually fine in STM; if a particular build lesson proves recurringly useful, promote it to `ltm` later (the consolidation pass also handles this automatically based on access patterns).

**What happens if you call this twice in the same day with the same topic?**
Two cases:
- **Same ID (deterministic)** → `store_memory` upserts. Second call overwrites the first. The duplicate-detector won't fire because the ID matches — it's treated as an update, not a new entry.
- **Auto-generated IDs** → you get two distinct memories with near-identical embeddings. The pre-store similarity check will warn ("near-duplicate detected"), but it doesn't block the write. You end up with duplicate noise that has to be cleaned up via `merge_memories` later.

**How would you handle that duplicate scenario in CI?**
Three viable strategies, in order of preference:

1. **Deterministic ID + append-on-collision** (shown above) — preserves all build outcomes for the day in a single rolling memory. Best when you want a daily build journal.
2. **Deterministic ID + last-write-wins** — simpler; just always upsert. Good when only the latest build matters (e.g., post-merge builds where earlier runs are obsolete).
3. **Per-build unique ID + post-hoc merge** — let each build store its own memory (`reflect-ci-build-outcome-2026-05-06-{buildNumber}`), then run `merge_memories` nightly to collapse them. Highest fidelity but most moving parts.

For CI, I'd default to **option 2** (last-write-wins) unless you specifically want the audit trail of every run, in which case use option 1. Avoid option 3 unless you already have a nightly maintenance job — duplicate accumulation in `stm` will just bloat search results until decay kicks in.

