So `Flush()` falsely reports "everything is persisted" while a write is still mid-flight. Same bug for shutdown ordering: caller flushes, disposes other things, the I/O lands afterward (or doesn't).

There's also a smaller issue: the inner `_pendingSearchIndexTimer?.Dispose()` disposes the very timer whose callback is running. Harmless on .NET's `System.Threading.Timer` (it allows self-dispose), but it's relying on that nuance — better to just set the field to null and let the outer scheduler dispose any replacement.

